06527nam a22008655i 9789048540266DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485402667 a10.1515/97890485402662doi  a(DE-B1597)583121  a(OCoLC)1247660706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a305.322300aTrans and Genderqueer Subjects in Medieval Hagiography /ced. by Blake Gutt, Alicia Spencer-Hall. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (342 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHagiography Beyond Tradition ;v200tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tFollowing the Traces. Reassessing the Status Quo, Reinscribing Trans and Genderqueer Realities -- t1 Assigned Female at Death -- t2 Inherited Futures and Queer Privilege -- t3 Juana de la Cruz -- t4 Non-Standard Masculinity and Sainthood in Niketas David's Life of Patriarch Ignatios -- tPeripheral Vision(s). Objects, Images, and Identities -- t5 Gender-Querying Christ's Wounds -- t6 Illuminating Queer Gender Identity in the Manuscripts of the Vie de sainte Eufrosine -- t7 The Queerly Departed -- tGenre, Gender, and Trans Textualities -- t8 St Eufrosine's Invitation to Gender Transgression -- t9 Holy Queer and Holy Cure -- t10 The Authentic Lives of Transgender Saints -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume presents an interdisciplinary examination of trans and genderqueer subjects in medieval hagiography. Scholarship has productively combined analysis of medieval literary texts with modern queer theory - yet, too often, questions of gender are explored almost exclusively through a prism of sexuality, rather than gender identity. This volume moves beyond such limitations, foregrounding the richness of hagiography as a genre integrally resistant to limiting binaristic categories, including rigid gender binaries. The collection showcases scholarship by emerging trans and genderqueer authors, as well as the work of established researchers. Working at the vanguard of historical trans studies, these scholars demonstrate the vital and vitally political nature of their work as medievalists. This volume enables the re-creation of a lineage linking modern trans and genderqueer individuals to their medieval ancestors, providing models of queer identity where much scholarship has insisted there were none, and re-establishing the place of non-normative gender in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHagiography, gender, religion, transgender, queer theory.1 aBychowski, M. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColwill, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijk, Mathilde van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElphick, Kevin C. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutt, Blake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutt, Blake, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcLoughlin, Caitlyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Martha G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgden, Amy V.